Quality of Service (QoS) in MQTT defines how reliably messages are delivered between the publisher and subscriber.

QoS Level	Description	Reliability
QoS 0 – At most once	Message is sent only once. No acknowledgment is received. The message may be lost.	Lowest
QoS 1 – At least once	Message is delivered at least once. The receiver sends an acknowledgment (ACK). Duplicate messages may occur.	Medium
QoS 2 – Exactly once	Message is delivered exactly once using a four-step handshake. No message loss or duplication occurs.	Highest
QoS Levels
QoS 0 (At most once):
Fastest communication.
No guarantee of message delivery.
Suitable for non-critical data.
QoS 1 (At least once):
Ensures the message reaches the receiver.
Duplicate messages are possible.
Suitable for most IoT applications.
QoS 2 (Exactly once):
Guarantees that each message is delivered exactly one time.
Highest reliability but has more network overhead.
Which QoS for an IoT Water Level Monitoring System?

Recommended: QoS 1 (At least once).

Reason:

Water level data should reliably reach the cloud or monitoring system.
If a duplicate message is received, it usually does not cause major problems because the latest sensor reading can simply overwrite the previous one.
QoS 1 provides a good balance between reliability, speed, and network usage.
QoS 2 is more reliable but adds extra communication overhead and is generally unnecessary for periodic water level readings.

Conclusion:
For an IoT water level monitoring system, QoS 1 (At least once) is the best choice because it ensures reliable message delivery while keeping network overhead low.
